5e9a3981-5d45-4880-a45e-5546b7f0ea81	Blockchain fundamentals & Ethereum basics 	Blockchain fundamentals & Ethereum basics 	4b3afb5b-3dd2-44e3-8ac9-2a95515a3616	\N	completed	medium	\N	\N	intern	4b3afb5b-3dd2-44e3-8ac9-2a95515a3616	2026-05-08 05:20:07.79	2026-05-08 05:20:07.79	2026-05-07 13:55:45.935	2026-05-08 05:20:07.79	2ba371fd-2faa-4e2b-a786-b040566ff81d	Blockchain fundamentals & Ethereum basics \n\n\nBlockchain fundamentals & Ethereum basics \nBlockchain Fundamentals\nWhat is Blockchain?\nA blockchain is a decentralized and distributed digital ledger that stores data in blocks connected in a chain. Each block contains:\nData (transactions or records)\nHash of the current block\nHash of the previous block\nBecause every block is linked to the previous one, altering data becomes extremely difficult.\nKey Features of Blockchain\nDecentralization\nNo single authority controls the network.\nData is shared across many computers (nodes).\nTransparency\nTransactions are visible to all participants in public blockchains.\nImmutability\nOnce data is added, it is nearly impossible to change.\nSecurity\nUses cryptographic hashing and consensus mechanisms.\nDistributed Ledger\nEvery node maintains a copy of the blockchain.\nComponents of Blockchain\n1. Block\nA block contains:\nBlock number\nTimestamp\nTransaction data\nPrevious block hash\nCurrent block hash\nNonce (used in mining)\n2. Hash\nA hash is a unique digital fingerprint generated using cryptographic algorithms like SHA-256.\nExample:\nInput: Hello\nOutput: 185f8db32271fe25f561a6fc938b2e264306ec304eda518007d1764826381969\nEven a tiny change in input changes the hash completely.\n3. Nodes\nDevices connected to the blockchain network.\nTypes:\nFull nodes\nLight nodes\nMiner nodes\n4. Consensus Mechanisms\nUsed to validate transactions.\nCommon mechanisms:\nProof of Work (PoW) – used earlier by Ethereum and still used by Bitcoin\nProof of Stake (PoS) – currently used by Ethereum\nTypes of Blockchain\nType\nDescription\nPublic Blockchain\nOpen to everyone\nPrivate Blockchain\nControlled by one organization\nConsortium Blockchain\nManaged by a group\nHybrid Blockchain\nCombination of public and private\nEthereum Basics\nWhat is Ethereum?\nEthereum is an open-source blockchain platform that allows developers to build decentralized applications (DApps) and smart contracts.\nCreated by Vitalik Buterin in 2015.\nUnlike Bitcoin, Ethereum is programmable.\nEther (ETH)\nETH is the native cryptocurrency of Ethereum.\nUses:\nPaying transaction fees\nRunning smart contracts\nStaking in PoS\nSmart Contracts\nSmart contracts are self-executing programs stored on the blockchain.\nFeatures:\nAutomatic execution\nNo intermediaries\nTransparent and secure\nExample:\n​\nEthereum Virtual Machine (EVM)\nThe EVM is the runtime environment that executes smart contracts on Ethereum.\nResponsibilities:\nExecutes bytecode\nMaintains blockchain state\nEnsures deterministic execution\nGas in Ethereum\nGas is the fee required to perform operations on Ethereum.\nUsed for:\nTransactions\nSmart contract execution\nData storage\nFormula:\n\\text{Transaction Fee} = \\text{Gas Used} \\times \\text{Gas Price}\nHigher gas price → Faster transaction confirmation.\nEthereum Accounts\n1. Externally Owned Account (EOA)\nControlled by private keys\nUsed by users\n2. Contract Account\nControlled by smart contract code\nEthereum Merge\nIn 2022, Ethereum moved from Proof of Work to Proof of Stake through an event called:\nThe Merge\nBenefits:\nReduced energy consumption\nBetter scalability foundation\nImproved sustainability\nApplications of Ethereum\nDecentralized Finance (DeFi)\nNFTs\nSupply Chain Management\nVoting Systems\nGaming\nIdentity Verification\nAdvantages of Ethereum\nDecentralized\nSecure\nProgrammable\nLarge developer ecosystem\nLimitations\nGas fees can be high\nScalability challenges\nSmart contract vulnerabilities\nDifference Between Bitcoin and Ethereum\nFeature\nBitcoin\nEthereum\nPurpose\nDigital currency\nSmart contract platform\nNative Coin\nBTC\nETH\nSmart Contracts\nLimited\nSupported\nConsensus\nPoW\nPoS\nLaunch Year\n2009\n2015\nSimple Workflow of Ethereum Transaction\nUser initiates transaction\nTransaction is broadcast to network\nValidators verify transaction\nTransaction added to block\nBlock added to blockchain\nState updated across network	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N
